Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Template Designer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/template-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/template-designer-6-7)

When you create a new template (see [New Template](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-actions-1-1#new-template)), you can either start with a minimal blank template or you can create a copy of a master template. Considering that many templates in your project will likely have several common elements (references to page masters, template parts, styles; maybe some common headers and footers) it saves time and effort to define these elements once and start from there rather than from scratch.

## Settings for Master Templates
You need to define where your master templates are stored before Template Designer can use them. You can define any number of storage locations for your master templates, although in most cases you likely only need one directory. Consider whether you are working on Infinica templates alone or in a team, and whether you are using a single computer or several computers in a network. Depending on these scenarios, you may want to pick a folder on your machine, or on a network drive, or in the Doxee Content Repository.

Open the Template Designer preferences (Edit &gt; Preferences) and select *Master Templates*. Click *Add *and use the dialog to pick a folder.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 180. Master Templates Preferences*

Any Infinica template that you store to any of the defined locations, including sub-directories, can be used as a master template when creating a new template. They will be listed in the *Create from master template *section:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 181. Pick Master Template*

Selecting one of the master templates will store a copy of it, rather than a blank template, at the target location you select.

## References within Master Templates
It is quite common for master templates to have references to other files (with page masters, template parts, styles; also images, XML data files, ). There are two ways to treat these references when making a copy of a master template:

- Make a copy of the referenced file, too, and store it along the new template. The exact storage location and file name for the referenced file is determined by the options in the preferences (see above).

- Keep the new template referencing the original file.

In both cases, the reference path within the new template is adapted so that the correct file is referenced.

The creator of a master template can control the behaviour of a reference by setting the *copy-with-master *property on the referencing element:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 182. copy-with-master*

Copying referenced files works transitively, which means that references from within copied files are treated the same way as references in the master template itself.

## Review and Confirm File Copying
As soon as referenced files are copied, creating a new template from a master template involves copying more than one file. Template Designer follows the preferences and naming conventions to calculate target locations and file names for them. Several possible situations need to be considered:

- References may be broken, which means the referenced file does not exist.

- The copy target may already exist.

- Several referenced files may end up being copied to the same target file. Suffixes will be appended as needed.

- The user may not be allowed to write to some target locations.

For these reasons, the user will be notified of any issues and will be asked to review the list of source and target files:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 183. Master Template File List*

The user can redirect files or remove files from the copy list.

The new template will be created at the selected target location and opened in the editor after clicking *OK*.
